  511:      * ("base" and "top") to the slots themselves.  So, both a
  512:      * successful pop and poll mainly entail a CAS of a slot from
  513:      * non-null to null.  Because we rely on CASes of references, we
  514:      * do not need tag bits on base or top.  They are simple ints as
  515:      * used in any circular array-based queue (see for example
  516:      * ArrayDeque).  Updates to the indices must still be ordered in a
  517:      * way that guarantees that top == base means the queue is empty,
  518:      * but otherwise may err on the side of possibly making the queue
  519:      * appear nonempty when a push, pop, or poll have not fully
  520:      * committed. Note that this means that the poll operation,
  521:      * considered individually, is not wait-free. One thief cannot
  522:      * successfully continue until another in-progress one (or, if
  523:      * previously empty, a push) completes.  However, in the
  524:      * aggregate, we ensure at least probabilistic non-blockingness.
  525:      * If an attempted steal fails, a thief always chooses a different
  526:      * random victim target to try next. So, in order for one thief to
  527:      * progress, it suffices for any in-progress poll or new push on
  528:      * any empty queue to complete. (This is why we normally use
  529:      * method pollAt and its variants that try once at the apparent
  530:      * base index, else consider alternative actions, rather than
  531:      * method poll.)
  532:      *
  533:      * This approach also enables support of a user mode in which local
  534:      * task processing is in FIFO, not LIFO order, simply by using
  535:      * poll rather than pop.  This can be useful in message-passing
  536:      * frameworks in which tasks are never joined.  However neither
  537:      * mode considers affinities, loads, cache localities, etc, so
  538:      * rarely provide the best possible performance on a given
  539:      * machine, but portably provide good throughput by averaging over
  540:      * these factors.  (Further, even if we did try to use such
  541:      * information, we do not usually have a basis for exploiting it.
  542:      * For example, some sets of tasks profit from cache affinities,
  543:      * but others are harmed by cache pollution effects.)
  544:      *
  545:      * WorkQueues are also used in a similar way for tasks submitted
  546:      * to the pool. We cannot mix these tasks in the same queues used
  547:      * for work-stealing (this would contaminate lifo/fifo
  548:      * processing). Instead, we randomly associate submission queues
  549:      * with submitting threads, using a form of hashing.  The
  550:      * ThreadLocal Submitter class contains a value initially used as
  551:      * a hash code for choosing existing queues, but may be randomly
  552:      * repositioned upon contention with other submitters.  In
  553:      * essence, submitters act like workers except that they are
  554:      * restricted to executing local tasks that they submitted (or in
  555:      * the case of CountedCompleters, others with the same root task).
  556:      * However, because most shared/external queue operations are more
  557:      * expensive than internal, and because, at steady state, external
  558:      * submitters will compete for CPU with workers, ForkJoinTask.join
  559:      * and related methods disable them from repeatedly helping to
  560:      * process tasks if all workers are active.  Insertion of tasks in
  561:      * shared mode requires a lock (mainly to protect in the case of
  562:      * resizing) but we use only a simple spinlock (using bits in
  563:      * field qlock), because submitters encountering a busy queue move
  564:      * on to try or create other queues -- they block only when
  565:      * creating and registering new queues.
  566:      *
  567:      * Management
  568:      * ==========
  569:      *
  570:      * The main throughput advantages of work-stealing stem from
  571:      * decentralized control -- workers mostly take tasks from
  572:      * themselves or each other. We cannot negate this in the
  573:      * implementation of other management responsibilities. The main
  574:      * tactic for avoiding bottlenecks is packing nearly all
  575:      * essentially atomic control state into two volatile variables
  576:      * that are by far most often read (not written) as status and
  577:      * consistency checks.
  578:      *
  579:      * Field "ctl" contains 64 bits holding all the information needed
  580:      * to atomically decide to add, inactivate, enqueue (on an event
  581:      * queue), dequeue, and/or re-activate workers.  To enable this
  582:      * packing, we restrict maximum parallelism to (1<<15)-1 (which is
  583:      * far in excess of normal operating range) to allow ids, counts,
  584:      * and their negations (used for thresholding) to fit into 16bit
  585:      * fields.
  586:      *
  587:      * Field "plock" is a form of sequence lock with a saturating
  588:      * shutdown bit (similarly for per-queue "qlocks"), mainly
  589:      * protecting updates to the workQueues array, as well as to
  590:      * enable shutdown.  When used as a lock, it is normally only very
  591:      * briefly held, so is nearly always available after at most a
  592:      * brief spin, but we use a monitor-based backup strategy to
  593:      * block when needed.
  594:      *
  595:      * Recording WorkQueues.  WorkQueues are recorded in the
  596:      * "workQueues" array that is created upon first use and expanded
  597:      * if necessary.  Updates to the array while recording new workers
  598:      * and unrecording terminated ones are protected from each other
  599:      * by a lock but the array is otherwise concurrently readable, and
  600:      * accessed directly.  To simplify index-based operations, the
  601:      * array size is always a power of two, and all readers must
  602:      * tolerate null slots. Worker queues are at odd indices. Shared
  603:      * (submission) queues are at even indices, up to a maximum of 64
  604:      * slots, to limit growth even if array needs to expand to add
  605:      * more workers. Grouping them together in this way simplifies and
  606:      * speeds up task scanning.
  607:      *
  608:      * All worker thread creation is on-demand, triggered by task
  609:      * submissions, replacement of terminated workers, and/or
  610:      * compensation for blocked workers. However, all other support
