  561:      * shared mode requires a lock (mainly to protect in the case of
  562:      * resizing) but we use only a simple spinlock (using bits in
  563:      * field qlock), because submitters encountering a busy queue move
  564:      * on to try or create other queues -- they block only when
  565:      * creating and registering new queues.
  566:      *
  567:      * Management
  568:      * ==========
  569:      *
  570:      * The main throughput advantages of work-stealing stem from
  571:      * decentralized control -- workers mostly take tasks from
  572:      * themselves or each other. We cannot negate this in the
  573:      * implementation of other management responsibilities. The main
  574:      * tactic for avoiding bottlenecks is packing nearly all
  575:      * essentially atomic control state into two volatile variables
  576:      * that are by far most often read (not written) as status and
  577:      * consistency checks.
  578:      *
  579:      * Field "ctl" contains 64 bits holding all the information needed
  580:      * to atomically decide to add, inactivate, enqueue (on an event
  581:      * queue), dequeue, and/or re-activate workers.  To enable this
  582:      * packing, we restrict maximum parallelism to (1<<15)-1 (which is
  583:      * far in excess of normal operating range) to allow ids, counts,
  584:      * and their negations (used for thresholding) to fit into 16bit
  585:      * fields.
  586:      *
  587:      * Field "plock" is a form of sequence lock with a saturating
  588:      * shutdown bit (similarly for per-queue "qlocks"), mainly
  589:      * protecting updates to the workQueues array, as well as to
  590:      * enable shutdown.  When used as a lock, it is normally only very
  591:      * briefly held, so is nearly always available after at most a
  592:      * brief spin, but we use a monitor-based backup strategy to
  593:      * block when needed.
  594:      *
  595:      * Recording WorkQueues.  WorkQueues are recorded in the
  596:      * "workQueues" array that is created upon first use and expanded
  597:      * if necessary.  Updates to the array while recording new workers
  598:      * and unrecording terminated ones are protected from each other
  599:      * by a lock but the array is otherwise concurrently readable, and
  600:      * accessed directly.  To simplify index-based operations, the
  601:      * array size is always a power of two, and all readers must
  602:      * tolerate null slots. Worker queues are at odd indices. Shared
  603:      * (submission) queues are at even indices, up to a maximum of 64
  604:      * slots, to limit growth even if array needs to expand to add
  605:      * more workers. Grouping them together in this way simplifies and
  606:      * speeds up task scanning.
  607:      *
  608:      * All worker thread creation is on-demand, triggered by task
  609:      * submissions, replacement of terminated workers, and/or
  610:      * compensation for blocked workers. However, all other support
